1 - Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is the Bay Area's bike share system. Bay Area Bike Share was introduced in 2013 as a pilot program for the region, with 700 bikes and 70 stations across San Francisco and San Jose. Once expansion is complete, Ford GoBike will grow to 7,000 bikes across San Francisco, the East Bay and San Jose.

Ford GoBike, like other bike share systems, consists of a fleet of specially designed, sturdy and durable bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations throughout the city. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system, making them ideal for one-way trips. People use bike share to commute to work or school, run errands, get to appointments or social engagements and more. It's a fun, convenient and affordable way to get around.

The bikes are available for use 24 hours/day, 7 days/week, 365 days/year and riders have access to all bikes in the network when they become a member or purchase a pass.

1.1 - Preliminary Wrangling¶

The data includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data is from 2019. The total amount of data is 2.506.983 rides.

The list of documents that I will use for this analysis can be found in this page.

Data is saved in different documents, as a result all documents shall be downloaded programmatically and then combined in one single file.

# Create a function to download, extract and read the data
def get_data(url):
    
    # Import the data programmatically using 'requests'
    r = requests.get(url)
    
    # Create empty dataframe
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    # Name of the zip file
    name_zip_file = url.split('/')[-1]
    
    # Name of the CSV file
    name_file = name_zip_file.split('.')[0] + ".csv"
    
    # Save the data in the current directory
    with open (name_zip_file, 'wb') as file:
        
        # Save the ZIP file
        file.write(r.content)
        
        # Unzip the zip file
        zf = zipfile.ZipFile(name_zip_file) 
        
        # Read the CSV file and save the result in a dataframe
        df = pd.read_csv(zf.open(name_file))
        
        # Before returning the data I will remove the column "rental_access_method" if it exist
        if 'rental_access_method' in df.columns:
            df.drop('rental_access_method', axis = 1, inplace = True)
            
        # Before returning the data I will remove the column "bike_share_for_all_trip" if it exist
        if 'bike_share_for_all_trip' in df.columns:
            df.drop('bike_share_for_all_trip', axis = 1, inplace = True)
            
    # Return the dataframe
    return(df)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In the dataframe bike_data there are in total 2,506,983 entries and 13 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id,user_type).

Most of the variables are numeric except for the start_station_name, end_station_name and user type.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I have special interest in start and end of rides. Users characteristics between Customer and Subscriber, day of weeks with high usage. The main goal is to identify the customer comsumption patterns of bike riding.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The start and end times, and related time-based information will be utilized heavily. I will use the customer related data, as well as the distance to understand the user-driven data behind each ride to gain more Subscribers.

# Change datatypes of dates
bike_data['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_data['start_time'])
bike_data['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_data['end_time'])

# Change the datatypes of the ids from int to string
bike_data['start_station_id'] = bike_data['start_station_id'].astype(int).astype(str)
bike_data['end_station_id'] = bike_data['end_station_id'].astype(int).astype(str)
bike_data['bike_id'] = bike_data['bike_id'].astype(str)

# Calculate the duration in hours
bike_data['duration_hour'] = bike_data['duration_sec']/3600

# Get the day, month, year, hour from the start and end time
bike_data['start_year'] = bike_data['start_time'].apply(lambda x: x.year)
bike_data['start_month'] = bike_data['start_time'].apply(lambda x: x.month)
bike_data['start_day'] = bike_data['start_time'].apply(lambda x: x.day)
bike_data['start_hour'] = bike_data['start_time'].apply(lambda x: x.hour)
bike_data['end_year'] = bike_data['end_time'].apply(lambda x: x.year)
bike_data['end_month'] = bike_data['end_time'].apply(lambda x: x.month)
bike_data['end_day'] = bike_data['end_time'].apply(lambda x: x.day)
bike_data['end_hour'] = bike_data['end_time'].apply(lambda x: x.hour)
In [21]:
# Function to get the month name from the month number
def get_month_name(month):
    list_months = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
    return(list_months[month-1])

# Create new column with the name of the month
bike_data['start_month_name'] = bike_data['start_month'].apply(lambda month: get_month_name(month))
bike_data['end_month_name'] = bike_data['end_month'].apply(lambda month: get_month_name(month))

# Monthly usage of the Baywheels Bike system
graph = sns.catplot(data = bike_data, x = 'start_month_name', kind = 'count', color = no_color, aspect=1.25, height=5);

graph.set_axis_labels('Month', 'Number of Bike Trips'),
graph.fig.suptitle('Baywheels Usage by Month', y = 1.05, fontsize = 12);
graph.set_xticklabels(rotation=75);

The most popular month is March, with October as the second most popular. April is the third the most popular month to use the baywheels bike system. The weather in San Francisco is best in the mid-late summer and usually stays sunny until returning to its usual foggy weather in the late autumn/early winter months.

Tuesdays and Thursdays seem to be the most popular days for using the bike sharing system, however Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays are very close to the Tues/Thursdays numbers. The usage drops significantly on Saturdays and Sundays suggesting the Baywheels bike share system is used primarily for commuting purposes during working days.

Winter months are the worst for the bike sharing system for both groups.

Customers: demand is high around summertime, reaching its peak in December. Customers are most probably tourists, or the occasional riders who visit the Bay Area.

Subscribers: the highest demand is from March till October. Subscribers are most likely riders using the bikes for their daily commute.

ax[1].set_title('Number of each type os user for each end hour in 2019');

In this case, as we saw before, there is a high demand at 8-9 am and then at 5 - 6 pm. Basically when the people start and end of the work. If we look on the subscribers and customers, we can see that there are more customers using it at the afternoon compared on the moorning.

They mainly rent bikes before and after a typical work or school day (8-9am and 5-6pm).

Subscribers increase during the summer and then it decrease on the winter

6 - Summary¶

This project is a good deal for Lyft and the users, because of the benefits, such as:

  • Environmentally friendly, budget friendly, and lifetsyle friendly.
  • Subscribers benefit from a health commuting choice
  • Customers have a sustainable option for touring the city.
  • Affordable and convenient transportation for all people

Renting a bike from the Baywheels Bike System is a fantastic way of moving around in the city, both for enjoyment and work. There are two types of clients using the system: Subscribers and Customers.

  • Subscribers are primarily daily commuters, having short trips to and from work, who rent a bike on weekdays at 8-9am and 5-6pm, and, occasionally around lunch time.
  • Customers are usually tourists or occassional riders who use the system mainly on weekends to explore the Bay Area.
